Baseball Prospectus, as well as other  analysts, are criticized for taking the human aspect out of the game of baseball. For example,  of the  wrote in an article that he did not want to hear or read about new-age baseball statistics any more (referencing  specifically), saying: <blockquote>"I suppose that if stats mongers want to sit at their computers and play with these things all day long, that’s their prerogative. But their attempt to introduce these new-age statistics into the game threatens to undermine most fans’ enjoyment of baseball and the human factor therein. People play baseball. Numbers don’t."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/02/27/sports/baseball/27chass.html?ex=1178683200&en=9d1d9a339e780519&ei=5070 |title=As Season Approaches, Some Topics Should Be Off Limits |publisher= |date= |accessdate=2007-05-07}}</ref></blockquote>
Nate Silver responded to this criticism in "An Open Letter to Murray Chass," including offering to meet Chass to watch a ballgame.<ref>Nate Silver, "An Open Letter to Murray Chass,"[http://www.baseballprospectus.com/unfiltered/?p=233 BaseballProspectus.com, February 27, 2007].</ref>  He expounded on the case for a positive impact of sabermetrics on the game of baseball in an article "How Sabermetrics Helps Build a Better Ballgame," published on Baseball Analysts.com.<ref>Nate Silver, "How Sabermetrics Helps Build a Better Ballgame," [http://baseballanalysts.com/archives/2007/05/how_sabermetric_1.php Baseball Analysts, May 10, 2007].</ref>
Another type of criticism comes from those who believe that by broadening its coverage and audience, Baseball Prospectus is becoming more like the mainstream media and losing what made it unique. In response to a question along this line in an on-line chat, Silver wrote:<blockquote>From a brand standpoint, we're more concerned about differentiation based on quality than differentiation based on where we fall on sort of the "saberpolitical" spectrum. We brought people like Kevin [Goldstein] and Bryan Smith on because [they're] the absolute best at what they do.<ref>Nate Silver, "Chat," [http://www.baseballprospectus.com/chat/chat.php?chatId=321 BaseballProspectus.com, June 27, 2007].</ref></blockquote>
